<item>
            <title>[THRIFT-125] OCaml libraries don&apos;t compile with 32-bit ocaml</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-125</link>
                <project id="12310800" key="THRIFT">Thrift</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;TBinaryProtocol.ml contains integers outside the range of 32-bit OCaml&apos;s native int type (specifically the version_mask and version_1). Additionally, when reading int32s off of the network it returns them as OCaml-native ints. This will behave wrong when an int &amp;gt;= 2**30 is sent over the network, as that will wrap on the OCaml side. I assume the author of this code used 64-bit OCaml, as the code won&apos;t even compile under 32-bit OCaml right now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In TBinaryProtocol 64-bit ints are kept as int64 objects. The same should be done with 32-bit int values.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;OCaml 3.10.2 (32-bit)&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
